anges**: After modifying ecard-carddav.el, the old compiled `ecard-carddav.elc` was being loaded. Server ORG still showed 23 chars / 30 bytes. Fixed by recompiling with `batch-byte-compile`.\n   - **Root cause: `decode-coding-region` no-op on unibyte buffers**: The previous session's fix (`decode-coding-region body-start (point-max) 'utf-8`) was completely ineffective because `url-retrieve-synchronously` returns a unibyte buffer, and `decode-coding-region` does nothing when `enable-multibyte-characters` is nil. Fixed by using `decode-coding-string` on the extracted body bytes.\n\n5. Problem Solving:\n   - **SOLVED: Chad Jones ORG encoding corruption** — Root cause identified and fixed. The `decode-coding-region` call in `ecard-carddav--parse-xml-response` was a no-op because the url.el response buffer is unibyte. Raw UTF-8 bytes passed through to `xml-parse-region`, which stored them as eight-bit characters (23 chars / 30 bytes) instead of properly decoded Unicode (19 chars / 23 bytes). Fix: use `decode-coding-string` to decode body bytes in a separate string, then parse XML in a temp buffer.\n   - **SOLVED: D: namespace prefix handling** — Added `D:` prefix case to `ecard-carddav--dom-by-tag-qname` for servers that use `D:` prefix for DAV namespace (doesn't affect Radicale but needed for other servers).\n   - **VERIFIED: All test suites pass** — 113 ecard tests + 19 sync tests = 132 tests, 0 failures.\n   - **NOT YET ADDRESSED: Whether `ecard-sync--fix-multibyte-request` advice is still needed** — Was reviewing this when summary was requested. The advice handles the PUT direction (preventing multibyte concat corruption in `url-http-create-request`). It may still be needed for interactive Emacs where headers are multibyte.\n\n6. All user messages:\n   - The initial message was a continuation from a previous conversation with the full session summary, including the instruction: \"Please continue the conversation from where we left it off without asking the user any f